description:
This research assesses the Ozone Depletion Global Index (ODGI) for the years 2024 and 2025 by examining long-lived ozone-depleting substances (ODSs) that are governed by the Montreal Protocol. Surface-based observations of 15 significant chlorine- and bromine-containing compounds yield precise estimates of their stratospheric contributions through the Equivalent Effective Stratospheric Chlorine (EESC) metric. The ODGI is computed independently for the mid-latitude and Antarctic stratospheres, taking into account region-specific photochemical degradation rates, average atmospheric age, and the comparative ozone-depleting efficiency of bromine relative to chlorine.  
 &nbsp; 
  The results indicate that EESC concentrations in the Antarctic stratosphere remain high due to prolonged isolation periods and reduced mixing, leading to a slower recovery in contrast to mid-latitude regions. In comparison, mid-latitude EESC values have decreased more swiftly, indicative of faster atmospheric transport and a heightened response to reductions in short-lived halocarbons. Furthermore, the research emphasizes recent trends in greenhouse gases: levels of methane and nitrous oxide are increasing at accelerating rates, while the radiative forcing from CFCs and HCFCs has either stabilized or decreased, counterbalanced by a rise in HFCs. These trends highlight the intricate interactions between chemical regulation, atmospheric transport, and the recovery of ozone.

